# Angular Built-in Directives – Single File Explanation

This document explains **Angular built-in directives**, their purpose, types, and usage with clear examples.

---

## What is a Directive in Angular?

A **directive** is a class that adds **behavior or modifies the DOM**.

Angular uses directives to:

* Add/remove elements
* Change appearance
* Handle conditional rendering
* Repeat elements dynamically

---

## Types of Built-in Directives

Angular has **three main types** of built-in directives:

1. **Structural Directives** – change DOM structure
2. **Attribute Directives** – change appearance/behavior
3. **Component Directives** – directives with templates

---

## 1. Structural Directives

Structural directives **add or remove elements from the DOM**.
They always start with `*`.

### `*ngIf`

Conditionally adds/removes elements.

```html
<div *ngIf="isLoggedIn">Welcome User</div>
```

---

### `*ngIf` with else

```html
<div *ngIf="isLoggedIn; else guest">Welcome</div>
<ng-template #guest>Please Login</ng-template>
```

---

### `*ngFor`

Repeats elements for each item in a collection.

```html
<li *ngFor="let item of items; index as i">
  {{ i }} - {{ item }}
</li>
```

---

### `*ngSwitch`

Used for multiple conditional cases.

```html
<div [ngSwitch]="role">
  <p *ngSwitchCase="'admin'">Admin</p>
  <p *ngSwitchCase="'user'">User</p>
  <p *ngSwitchDefault>Guest</p>
</div>
```

---

## 2. Attribute Directives

Attribute directives **change the appearance or behavior** of an element.
They do NOT add or remove elements.

---

### `ngClass`

Adds/removes CSS classes dynamically.

```html
<div [ngClass]="{ active: isActive, disabled: isDisabled }">
  Status
</div>
```

---

### `ngStyle`

Applies inline styles dynamically.

```html
<div [ngStyle]="{ color: textColor, 'font-size': fontSize + 'px' }">
  Styled Text
</div>
```

---

### `ngModel`

Enables two-way data binding (forms).

```html
<input [(ngModel)]="username">
```

⚠ Requires importing `FormsModule`.

---

## 3. Component Directives

Components are directives **with templates**.

```ts
@Component({
  selector: 'app-user',
  template: '<p>User Component</p>'
})
export class UserComponent {}
```

Usage:

```html
<app-user></app-user>
```

---

## Special Angular Elements

### `<ng-container>`

Groups elements **without adding extra DOM nodes**.

```html
<ng-container *ngIf="isVisible">
  <p>Line 1</p>
  <p>Line 2</p>
</ng-container>
```

---

### `<ng-template>`

Defines a template that is rendered conditionally.

```html
<ng-template #loading>
  Loading...
</ng-template>
```

---

## Summary Table

| Directive   | Type       | Purpose               |
| ----------- | ---------- | --------------------- |
| `*ngIf`     | Structural | Conditional rendering |
| `*ngFor`    | Structural | Looping               |
| `*ngSwitch` | Structural | Multiple conditions   |
| `ngClass`   | Attribute  | Dynamic CSS classes   |
| `ngStyle`   | Attribute  | Dynamic styles        |
| `ngModel`   | Attribute  | Two-way binding       |

---

## Best Practices

* Use `*ngIf` instead of hiding elements with CSS
* Use `trackBy` with `*ngFor` for performance
* Avoid heavy logic inside templates
* Prefer attribute directives for styling

---

## One-line Memory Rule

> Structural directives change the DOM, attribute directives change appearance, components are directives with templates.

---

This file covers **all commonly used Angular built-in directives** in one place.
